TY  - JOUR
T1  - Make, Buy, or Ally: A Transaction Cost Theory Meta-Analysis
AU  - Geyskens, Inge
AU  - Steenkamp, Jan-Benedict E. M.
AU  - Kumar, Nirmalya
Y1  - 2006/06/01
PY  - 2006
DA  - 2006/06/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/amj.2006.21794670
DO  - 10.5465/amj.2006.21794670
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 519
EP  - 543
VL  - 49
IS  - 3
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - Since the publication of Williamson's Markets and Hierarchies, many empirical articles have investigated the tenets of transaction cost theory. Using meta-analytic techniques, we quantitatively synthesized and evaluated transaction cost-based empirical research on organizational boundary (make, buy, or ally) decisions. We found strong support for the theory for both make versus buy and ally versus buy decisions. However, we did not find evidence that asset specificity had stronger predictive power than uncertainty. Hierarchical and relational governance appropriately aligned with transaction dimensions both led to enhanced performance. On the basis of our meta-analysis, we provide directions for future research.
AB  - Since the publication of Williamson's Markets and Hierarchies, many empirical articles have investigated the tenets of transaction cost theory. Using meta-analytic techniques, we quantitatively synthesized and evaluated transaction cost-based empirical research on organizational boundary (make, buy, or ally) decisions. We found strong support for the theory for both make versus buy and ally versus buy decisions. However, we did not find evidence that asset specificity had stronger predictive power than uncertainty. Hierarchical and relational governance appropriately aligned with transaction dimensions both led to enhanced performance. On the basis of our meta-analysis, we provide directions for future research.
SN  - 0001-4273
M3  - doi: 10.5465/amj.2006.21794670
UR  - https://doi.org/10.5465/amj.2006.21794670
Y2  - 2026/04/24
